        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>La Union is five to six hours up the TPLEX from Quezon City and it has been the surf capital of the Philippines for over a decade. Most travelers know San Juan and the surf strip, but the province stretches from Bauang in the south to Bacnotan in the north, and the actual tourist spots cover surf beaches, waterfalls, a Taoist temple, and one of the most-photographed halo-halo shops in the north.</p>
<p>This is a calm DIY weekend list, not a top 10 ranking. The spots below are the ones worth the jeepney or tricycle ride. Tara, the kwento starts at the surf strip.</p>
<h2>San Juan Surf Beach (Urbiztondo)</h2>
<p>Urbiztondo is the surf strip of San Juan and the heart of the La Union scene. Two-hour beginner lessons are available year-round, and the surf-school operators are clustered along the same 300-meter stretch so you can walk down the beach, watch a few sessions, and pick whoever feels right. The waves from October to March are the bigger ones and pull a more serious surf crowd. April to September is calmer, smaller, and friendlier for first-timers.</p>
<p>Sunset at Urbiztondo is the social hour. Surf schools rinse the boards, the bars start playing music, and the beach fills up with the surfer crowd plus the digital-nomad weekenders from Manila. Stay on the beach itself if you want this scene to be your weekend; stay in San Fernando city if you want quieter rooms with a 20-minute drive in.</p>
<h2>Tangadan Falls</h2>
<p>Tangadan is a 30-minute drive inland from San Juan, in the municipality of San Gabriel. It is a wide pool fed by a 10-meter waterfall and rimmed by jumping rocks. The trek in from the registration area takes around 20 minutes through farmland and a small river crossing, easy in trail runners.</p>
<p>Go early. The pool is in shade by late afternoon and the photos are flatter then. Tuesdays and Wednesdays are the quietest days; weekends from December to May get full. The locals charge a small registration fee at the trail head and a guide is mandatory.</p>
<h2>Ma-Cho Temple, San Fernando</h2>
<p>Ma-Cho is a Taoist temple set on a hill overlooking the San Fernando bay. It honors Mazu, the Chinese sea goddess, and it has the kind of dragon-tiled roofs and red-pillar courtyards you do not expect on a Philippine coastal hill. Free entry, modest dress code, and the climb up the stairs from the parking area takes around five minutes. Sunset is the best window for the bay view.</p>
<p>From the temple you can walk down to the San Fernando city center in about 15 minutes if you want to combine the visit with lunch. Most jeepneys from San Juan to San Fernando city drop off at the Ma-Cho stop along the highway.</p>
<h2>Halo-Halo de Iloko</h2>
<p>Halo-Halo de Iloko in San Fernando is the famous Ilocos halo-halo restaurant. The order to get is the halo-halo topped with longganisa-flavored ice cream, which sounds like a dare and turns out to be sulit. The shop is on the city's main road, walkable from Ma-Cho Temple, and the small dining area fills up by midday on weekends.</p>
<p>If you do not want the savory ice cream version, the regular Ilocos halo-halo with pinipig and corn is the safer order. They also serve full Ilocano lunches: bagnet, pinakbet with bagoong isda, and Ilocos longganisa. A real one-stop meal stop, especially if you are passing through San Fernando on the way north to Vigan.</p>
<h2>Bauang and Aringay Beaches</h2>
<p>Bauang is 20 minutes south of San Juan and it is the calmer family-resort coast. The sand is darker, the waves are smaller, and the resort row along the Paringao stretch has the swimming pools that kids actually use. If you are traveling with elders or small children, Bauang handles those needs better than the surf strip.</p>
<p>The Saint Peter and Saint Paul Parish Church (1607) in the Bauang town center is worth a 20-minute stop on the way through. Stone walls, plaza-facing, and a working parish that has stood through earthquakes, wars, and four centuries of weather.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Buses from Cubao or Pasay leave every hour. Partas, Genesis, and Victory Liner are the main operators. Overnight trip is 6 to 7 hours; daytime with TPLEX is 5 to 5.5 hours if traffic flows. Check schedules and book online with <a href="https://www.partas.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Partas</a> or <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a>. If you drive, TPLEX exit at Rosario then Manila North Road up to San Juan.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>The Ilocano food scene in La Union is the heaviest carb-and-pork experience in the country. Order Ilocos longganisa (vinegary, garlicky) for breakfast at any carinderia. Order bagnet (deep-fried pork belly) and pinakbet Ilocos-style with bagoong isda for lunch. For halo-halo, Halo-Halo de Iloko is the destination order. For coffee and a pizza, El Union Coffee Co. in San Juan is the surf-town landmark.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>October through March is the high surf season and the cool dry months. The waves are biggest in December and January. April through September is the calmer side with smaller waves; better for first-timer surfers and for swimming at Bauang. Avoid Holy Week unless you booked rooms three months out; the surf strip is at full capacity.</p>
<p>La Union is the rare Philippine destination that works year-round, just for different reasons each season. Plan around the waves if you surf; plan around the food if you do not.</p>
