        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Ilocos Norte is the dry, Spanish-baroque, windmill-and-lighthouse end of Luzon. Fly to Laoag in one hour fifteen minutes from Manila, then drive an 80-kilometer coastal road that strings together a UNESCO church, a 19th-century lighthouse, a wind farm, a white-rock formation, and a beach. Two days covers it without rushing.</p>
<p>This is the standard loop the locals call the Bangui-Pagudpud run, started from Laoag city as a base. The spots are spread along the coast so a van rental for one full day is the cleanest plan. Tara, here is the kwento by stop.</p>
<h2>Paoay Church (1710)</h2>
<p>Paoay Church is the most-photographed church in the north and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The earthquake-baroque buttresses on each side were built thick to handle the seismic activity that flattened lesser buildings across the centuries. Up close the coral-stone surface has a texture and a wear that no photo really captures.</p>
<p>The church is 20 minutes from Laoag city proper. Plaza-facing, free entry, working parish. The best photo light is mid-morning when the sun hits the front facade. The plaza has a row of stalls selling Paoay specialties: Ilocos empanada, sukang Iloko, and tupig (sticky rice grilled in banana leaves).</p>
<h2>La Paz Sand Dunes</h2>
<p>La Paz Sand Dunes is a 20-minute drive from Laoag, on the Suba area between the city and the West Philippine Sea. The dunes were the location used for the iconic Filipino films Himala and Panday. The 4x4 dune-bashing run includes a sandboarding stop on the steeper slopes; the standard run takes around 30 to 45 minutes.</p>
<p>Go early or go in late afternoon. Midday sun on the sand reflects like an oven and the dune-bashing is harder to enjoy with the heat. Sandboarding is the kind of thing that looks corny on Instagram and turns out genuinely fun in person, especially with a barkada.</p>
<h2>Bangui Windmills</h2>
<p>The Bangui windmills are 20 turbines lined along the beach of Bangui Bay, the first wind farm in Southeast Asia. The drive in is the actual highlight; the coastal road from Burgos curves down to the beach and the turbines come into view in a slow reveal. Park anywhere along the public road that fronts the beach, walk down to the sand, and the photos take themselves.</p>
<p>The wind here never stops. Bring a windbreaker even on a hot day. The beach itself is pebble-and-coarse-sand, not for swimming, but the long stretch with the turbines as backdrop is the postcard. Stay 30 minutes, then drive on to the lighthouse.</p>
<h2>Cape Bojeador Lighthouse</h2>
<p>Cape Bojeador Lighthouse is an 1892 brick tower on a hilltop in Burgos. The Spanish colonial government built it to mark the northwestern tip of Luzon. The climb up to the gallery is currently restricted but the base is open, the view to the Bangui coast is full, and the bricks themselves are worth the visit. Free entry, plus a small museum room about the lighthouse keepers who maintained the kerosene lamp before electrification.</p>
<p>It is 30 minutes north of Bangui along the same coastal road. Combine it with the Kapurpurawan stop in a single loop; the two are within 20 minutes of each other.</p>
<h2>Kapurpurawan Rock Formation</h2>
<p>Kapurpurawan is a stretch of white limestone sculpted by waves and wind over centuries. The rock is reached by a 10-minute walk from the parking area, with a short flight of stairs down to the coast. Up close the formations look like cresting waves frozen mid-curl. The locals will offer to take photos for tips.</p>
<p>Best around late afternoon when the light angles in low and the white rock glows orange. Mid-morning works too. Bring water, the walk back up the stairs in the sun is a heat test.</p>
<h2>Pagudpud (Saud and Blue Lagoon)</h2>
<p>Pagudpud is the northernmost beach stretch of Luzon, and the Saud and Blue Lagoon beaches are the two postcard coves. Saud is the calmer family beach, with the resort row strung along the curve of the bay. Blue Lagoon is the surfable side, with bigger waves from habagat season (June to October).</p>
<p>From Bangui to Pagudpud is around 40 minutes more. If you started the loop in Laoag at 7 AM, you should be in Pagudpud by mid-afternoon. Spend the night, return to Laoag the next morning. The 80-kilometer drive between Laoag and Pagudpud is the actual highlight, more than any single stop.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Laoag in one hour fifteen minutes with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a>. From Laoag airport, taxi or Grab to the city center is 15 minutes. For the coastal loop, hire a van for the day; the spots are too spread out for tricycles or jeepneys. Bus from Cubao to Laoag is 10 to 12 hours overnight.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>Ilocos empanada and longganisa from the Laoag public market are the breakfast order. Miki Batac (Ilocano noodle soup) is the specialty of Batac town, 30 minutes south of Laoag. Bagnet at La Preciosa or Herencia in Laoag. Dirty ice cream and dragon fruit shakes at the roadside stops on the Bangui-Pagudpud run.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to March is the cool, dry, festival-friendly window. The Pamulinawen Festival in early February has parades along Aurora Park in Laoag. April to May is hot but the surf in Pagudpud picks up. June to October is habagat season with high waves and possible road washouts on the coastal stretch.</p>
<p>Two days, one night is the realistic loop. Three days lets you slow down and add Vigan to the south on the return leg. Either way, Ilocos Norte rewards the calmer pace.</p>
