        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Vigan is the cleanest preserved Spanish-era town in the Philippines and one of three UNESCO World Heritage Sites in the country. Eight to ten hours from Manila by bus, or a 90-minute drive south from Laoag if you fly in. The cobblestones, the empanada stalls, and the dancing fountain at Plaza Salcedo are the headline. The rest of the city is a working Ilocano town that does not pretend.</p>
<p>This is a heritage walk you can do in one full day, two if you want the pottery workshops in San Vicente plus the Bantay Bell Tower up north. Tara, the kwento goes stop by stop.</p>
<h2>Calle Crisologo</h2>
<p>Calle Crisologo is the cobblestone heritage street, the postcard core of Vigan. Spanish-era ancestral houses line both sides, most of them still occupied by descendants of the original Ilocano-Chinese mestizo families. The street is closed to motorized traffic from 6 PM onward; calesas (horse-drawn carriages) run the route during the day for visitors.</p>
<p>Walk it twice in one trip. Once at 6 AM before the tour buses arrive, when the cobblestones are quiet and the morning light angles down the street. Then again at 9 PM when the heritage-house lamps come on and the calesas have thinned out. The postcard photos most travelers take are the 9 PM version; the 6 AM version is the one you keep.</p>
<h2>Vigan Cathedral and Plaza Salcedo</h2>
<p>The Saint Paul Metropolitan Cathedral (Vigan Cathedral) anchors the eastern end of the heritage core. It is a working parish, a former earthquake-baroque structure rebuilt and reinforced through the centuries, and the seat of the Archdiocese of Nueva Segovia. Free entry; cover shoulders if you are entering during a mass.</p>
<p>Plaza Salcedo in front of the cathedral hosts the nightly dancing fountain show, usually at 7:30 PM. The fountain runs water jets choreographed to music, with the cathedral lit up as the backdrop. It is the kind of thing that sounds corny and turns out to be a calm 15 minutes that ends the heritage walk nicely.</p>
<h2>Bantay Bell Tower</h2>
<p>Bantay Bell Tower is a 1591 freestanding bell tower 10 minutes north of Vigan in the town of Bantay. It is one of the oldest stone bell towers in the Philippines, separated from its parish church for fire safety in case the cathedral burned. Climb the wooden stairs to the top for an overview of the heritage core to the south and the Bantay rice fields to the north. Free entry.</p>
<p>The tower also served as a watchtower against pirates coming up the Mestizo River. The view from the top is the kind that explains the geography of Vigan in one frame.</p>
<h2>Crisologo Museum and Syquia Mansion</h2>
<p>The Crisologo Museum is the ancestral house of the Crisologo political family, kept as it was during their peak political years in the mid-20th century. It explains the post-Spanish era of Vigan, the period when the Ilocano-Chinese mestizo families built much of what you see on Calle Crisologo. Free entry, donations welcome.</p>
<p>The Syquia Mansion is the ancestral home of President Elpidio Quirino's wife. It is the other major heritage-house museum, with period furniture, family portraits, and a quiet courtyard. Both museums fit into one morning, and they explain the Calle Crisologo houses better than any walking tour.</p>
<h2>Hidden Garden and the Burnayan Pottery</h2>
<p>Hidden Garden is a lunch stop on the way to the San Vicente burnayan (pottery workshops). The restaurant is open-air, the menu is Ilocano (pinakbet, bagnet, poqui-poqui), and the garden setting is the kind of break the heritage-walk pace needs.</p>
<p>The burnayan workshops down the road are working pottery studios where craftsmen turn the local clay into burnay jars on foot-powered wheels. You can watch the process for a small entry fee. Some workshops let visitors try the wheel; the jars themselves are sold on site if you want a pasalubong that is heavier than empanada.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Bus from Cubao or Pasay to Vigan terminal is 8 to 10 hours overnight. Partas runs the most slots; book online with <a href="https://www.partas.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Partas</a> for the deluxe class. The cleaner trip is to fly Manila to Laoag in one hour fifteen minutes, then take a 90-minute van or bus south to Vigan. The TPLEX shortcut works if you drive your own car.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>Vigan empanada from the Plaza Burgos stalls is the headline order. The orange color comes from achuete, the crisp from a quick deep-fry, and the filling is grated papaya, longganisa, and an egg dropped in just before frying. Bagnet plus sukang Iloko at Cafe Leona on Calle Crisologo is the dinner order. Longganisa Vigan-style (garlicky, vinegary, smaller than Lucban) for breakfast at any carinderia.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to February is the cool, dry, festival-friendly window. Holy Week gets intense at Calle Crisologo; book rooms three months out if you want this season. May 1 to 3 is the Viva Vigan Binatbatan Festival of the Arts; expect packed sidewalks and full hotels.</p>
<p>One full day plus one night is the realistic minimum. Two days lets you fit Bantay, the museums, the burnayan, plus both the 6 AM and 9 PM Calle Crisologo windows without rushing. Vigan is a slow city, the kind that punishes the rushed traveler and rewards the calm one.</p>
