        'title' => 'Tourist Spots in Pangasinan: Bolinao, Alaminos, and the Hundred Islands',
        'slug' => 'tourist-spots-pangasinan-bolinao-alaminos-hundred-islands',
        'excerpt' => 'Pangasinan stretches from inland farming towns to Lingayen Gulf. Here is the calm DIY list: Hundred Islands, Patar Beach, Manaoag, Lingayen, plus the food.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Pangasinan stretches from the inland farming towns to the coast at Lingayen Gulf. The Hundred Islands National Park is the famous attraction, but the province also has Bolinao's white beaches, the Manaoag Marian pilgrimage shrine, and the Dagupan bangus that no other province's milkfish quite matches. Three and a half to four and a half hours from Quezon City via TPLEX, depending on which corner of the province you target.</p>
<p>Pangasinan is huge. Trying to do all the spots in one weekend means a lot of driving. Pick one base town, run the spots within an hour of it, then come back another weekend for the rest. Tara, the kwento goes by region.</p>
<h2>Hundred Islands National Park (Alaminos)</h2>
<p>Hundred Islands is the postcard attraction of Pangasinan: 124 small islands scattered across Lingayen Gulf, each different, each climbable in about 20 minutes. The full-day boat tour visits 4 to 6 of them, with stops for swimming, snorkeling, and a picnic lunch. Lucap Wharf in Alaminos is where the boats leave at 7 AM and return by 4 PM.</p>
<p>Governor's Island has the viewing tower with the panorama everyone photographs. Quezon Island is the largest accessible island with cottages and overnight camping. Marcos Island has the Imelda Cave you walk through. Children's Island has the shallow swim zone for families. The standard boat for 5 to 8 people covers the headline stops on a calm day.</p>
<h2>Patar Beach (Bolinao)</h2>
<p>Patar Beach is the long stretch of white-to-cream sand on the northern Pangasinan tip. It is a 4.5-hour drive from Quezon City via TPLEX, and the sand is closer to white than any other beach in the region (Pagudpud excluded). The best sunset spot is the rock outcrops at the southern end of the beach, not the resort-cluster center where most travelers pile up.</p>
<p>Bolinao itself is a small town that punches above its size. The same trip can fit the Cape Bolinao Lighthouse for sunset, the Bolinao Falls 1, 2, and 3 for the next morning's swim, and the 1609 St. James the Great Parish Church for a 20-minute history stop. Bolinao Falls 2 has the best swimming pool with a rope swing included.</p>
<h2>Cape Bolinao Lighthouse</h2>
<p>Cape Bolinao is a 19th-century lighthouse perched on a hilltop overlooking the West Philippine Sea. Free to climb at sunset; the steps up are paved and the gallery view of the Bolinao coast is the kind of thing that ends a day on the beach properly. The lighthouse is 15 minutes from Patar by tricycle, easy combination stop.</p>
<h2>Manaoag Shrine</h2>
<p>The Our Lady of Manaoag Shrine is the country's major Marian pilgrimage site. The basilica is in the town of Manaoag, an hour east of Dagupan and roughly two hours from Hundred Islands. Pilgrims come from all over the Philippines for novenas and the touching of the image. The grounds are open year-round; the queues are heaviest on weekends and during October (the Lady's feast month).</p>
<p>The shrine is a quieter visit if you go on a weekday morning. The Manaoag pasalubong stalls outside the basilica sell candles, religious medals, and the local bocayo (sweet coconut bars). Combine the visit with a Dagupan food stop on the way back.</p>
<h2>Lingayen Beach</h2>
<p>Lingayen is where MacArthur landed in 1945, and the long stretch of public beach there is a working town beach, not a resort destination. The Lingayen Capitol building (1918) faces the sea across a wide plaza; the architecture alone is worth a 20-minute walk. Locals run a sunset salakot crowd here on weekends, plus a row of carinderias along the beachfront for fresh seafood.</p>
<p>Lingayen is the provincial capital and the historical heart of Pangasinan. If you are doing a one-day passing trip, this is a calm middle stop between Dagupan and the Alaminos run.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>TPLEX from Quezon City is the standard route. Urdaneta exit is 3.5 hours; Bolinao is 4.5 hours; Alaminos is 4.5 hours. <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a>, Five Star, and Genesis run the buses from Cubao and Pasay; the trip takes 5 to 6 hours depending on the destination. Multiple operators have direct buses to Bolinao and Alaminos terminals.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>Pigar-pigar is the Dagupan stir-fried beef specialty; any pigaran stall in the city serves the right version with crispy fried onions. Bangus from the Dagupan side is the national milkfish standard; the city is the bangus capital of the Philippines. Puto Calasiao is the small, soft, steamed rice cake from the neighboring town of Calasiao. At Bolinao, the Patar Beach eateries serve fresh oysters and grilled fish straight from the morning catch.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May is the calm-sea season; this is when the island-hopping boats run reliably. June to October is typhoon season; the Hundred Islands boats cancel when the gulf gets rough, and the Pangasinan coast gets hit harder than most. The Bangus Festival in Dagupan in April is the local headline event; expect packed hotels.</p>
<p>Stay in Alaminos for the Hundred Islands. Stay in Bolinao for the beach and the lighthouse. Stay in Dagupan for the food and the Manaoag side trip. Trying to use one base for all three is the rookie move; pick one per weekend.</p>
