        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Laoag is the gateway city of Ilocos Norte: a 17th-century sinking bell tower, a small but solid heritage core, sand dunes 20 minutes out, and the best Ilocano food in the region. Fly in from Manila in just over an hour and you have a base for the Bangui-Pagudpud-Vigan loops. Most travelers pass through Laoag on the way north or south, but the city itself is worth a half day on foot.</p>
<p>This is the calm half-day walk plus the one quick van trip out to the dunes. You can do it in the morning, eat a long Ilocano lunch, then drive north for the Bangui loop in the afternoon. Tara, the kwento starts at the bell tower.</p>
<h2>Sinking Bell Tower</h2>
<p>The Sinking Bell Tower is the postcard stop of Laoag. The 17th-century brick tower sinks an inch a year into the soft soil of the Padsan riverbank. Built in 1612 by Augustinian friars, it once stood tall enough that a person on horseback could enter through the lower door. Now the door is partly buried and you can crouch through to enter the ground floor.</p>
<p>The tower is detached from the church it once served, the Saint William Cathedral, because the friars built it free-standing for fire safety. Free entry, climb up the wooden stairs to the bell chamber for the view of the city. Plaza-facing, with carinderias and pasalubong stalls along the streets that fan out from the base.</p>
<h2>Saint William Cathedral (Laoag Cathedral)</h2>
<p>Saint William Cathedral is the Ilocos Norte mother church and the seat of the Diocese of Laoag. The current building is the 1880 reconstruction after the 1707 original was damaged by earthquakes. The facade is Italian-Renaissance style, which is unusual for Ilocos where the earthquake-baroque style dominates. Free entry, working parish, plaza-facing.</p>
<p>Combine the cathedral and the bell tower in one 30-minute walk. They are within a five-minute walk of each other and the plaza between them is the social center of the old city.</p>
<h2>La Paz Sand Dunes</h2>
<p>La Paz Sand Dunes is 20 minutes from the city center, on the Suba area between Laoag and the West Philippine Sea. The dunes stretch for a few kilometers along the coast and they were the location for the iconic Filipino film Himala. The standard tour is a 4x4 dune-bashing run with a sandboarding stop on the steeper slopes, taking around 30 to 45 minutes.</p>
<p>Go early or in late afternoon to avoid the midday sand glare. The 4x4 operators are based at the Suba sand dune entrance; book the run on arrival or through any hotel concierge in the city. Sandboarding on a wooden board with a candle-waxed bottom is a genuinely fun barkada activity, the kind of thing that becomes the trip story.</p>
<h2>Museo Ilocos Norte</h2>
<p>Museo Ilocos Norte is a former tobacco warehouse turned into the regional museum, free entry. It explains the Ilocano cultural identity through the textiles (Ilocano-weaving traditions), the Tinguian-ethnic items from the highlands, and the Spanish-colonial history of Ilocos as a tobacco-monopoly region. Two hours covers the full exhibit.</p>
<p>The museum is a quick stop on the way out of the heritage core. It is the kind of place that adds context to everything else you saw on the walk; you understand the Sinking Bell Tower and the cathedral better after a museum stop than before.</p>
<h2>Tobacco Monopoly Monument and Aurora Park</h2>
<p>Aurora Park is the riverside walk along the Padsan River, with the 1786 Tobacco Monopoly Memorial as the central marker. The Spanish colonial government established the tobacco monopoly in Ilocos in 1782, which made the region economically central for the next century and built much of the wealth you see in the heritage houses around Vigan. The memorial is a calm 15-minute stop, plus the park itself is a working public space with vendors and benches under the trees.</p>
<p>Aurora Park hosts the Pamulinawen Festival parades in early February, the biggest Laoag cultural event of the year.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Laoag International Airport in one hour fifteen minutes. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a> run the most slots. From the airport, taxi or Grab to the city center is 15 minutes. Bus from Cubao or Pasay is 10 to 12 hours overnight; Partas runs the deluxe service.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>Laoag empanada from the public market vendors is the breakfast or merienda order. The orange color comes from achuete and the filling is grated papaya, longganisa, and an egg. Saramsam Ylocano serves the longganisa-and-garlic-rice plate that locals consider the proper Ilocano breakfast. Bagnet at La Preciosa or Herencia is the lunch order. For pasalubong, dragon fruit shakes from the Refmad Dragon Fruit Farm in Burgos (30 minutes north) are the right roadside stop on the way out.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to March is the cool, dry window. The Pamulinawen Festival in early February has parades along Aurora Park and a packed downtown. April to May is hot and dry; June to October is habagat season with rain and possible flight disruptions.</p>
<p>Half a day covers the heritage core and the museum. Add the sand dunes and you fill a full day. Stay in Laoag if you want a base for the Bangui-Pagudpud loop; stay in Pagudpud only if the beach is the main goal.</p>
