        'excerpt' => 'The San Juan bar strip starts after sunset and runs late. Here is the honest guide to the surf-town night scene, the bars worth a kwento, and how to get back.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>San Juan is the surf capital of the Philippines and the night scene runs hard from October through March. Five hours from Manila by bus, a row of surf hostels and post-sunset bars along Urbiztondo Beach, and waves that are consistent enough that beginners can learn from October through March. The 30-something digital-nomad crowd is the loudest voice here, but the town still feels like its own thing.</p>
<p>This is the honest barkada guide to the bars and the night scene. No marketing nonsense, no fake top-10 ranking, just the spots that actually have a kwento worth telling. Tara, let us start at the iconic one.</p>
<h2>Flotsam and Jetsam Hostel</h2>
<p>Flotsam and Jetsam is the iconic boutique-surf hostel and beach bar of San Juan, the spot that put La Union on every travel Instagram in the country. The bar fronts Urbiztondo Beach, the cocktails are competent, and the live-music nights pull a real crowd. The vibe is mid-20s to mid-30s, mixed local and expat, and the music leans into reggae, indie, and the occasional DJ set on bigger weekends.</p>
<p>Best window is sunset onward. Order a beer, watch the surfers finish their sessions, then stay for the live act that usually starts around 9 PM. The food is decent (surf-town comfort, not haute) but you come here for the scene and the location, not for fine dining.</p>
<h2>El Union Coffee Co.</h2>
<p>El Union is the surf-town landmark for daytime, but the early-evening hours pull a sit-down crowd that turns the cafe into a soft-bar setting until close. The pizzas are the real order; the local craft beers on tap are the surprise. The vibe is calmer than the beachfront bars, the kind of pre-game stop you do before walking down to the Urbiztondo strip later.</p>
<p>El Union closes earlier than the beach bars, usually by 10 or 11 PM. If you want a quieter night, this is the whole evening. If you want the loud one, this is the warm-up.</p>
<h2>The Surf Shack and the Urbiztondo Bar Row</h2>
<p>The Urbiztondo bar row is the cluster of post-surf bars that come alive after sunset. The Surf Shack, Vessel, and the open-air spots that change names every couple of years all sit within a 300-meter walk along the beachfront. The pattern is the same across all of them: cold beers, basic cocktails, surf-town food (sisig, nachos, calamares), and music that ranges from acoustic to DJ depending on the night.</p>
<p>Friday and Saturday nights are the peak, with the crowds spilling out onto the sand. Weeknight visits are calmer and the bars stay open later than most beach towns in the country. The scene is friendly; striking up a kwento with the people at the next table is the norm, not the exception.</p>
<h2>Makai Bowls and the Beachfront Snacks</h2>
<p>Makai Bowls and the row of beachfront food stalls are the late-night snack stops between bars. The acai bowls and the tuna sashimi from the Urbiztondo grills do the job at 11 PM when you need food but not a full sit-down meal. The grills serve fresh fish from the morning catch; the tuna sashimi plate is the order most barkadas split.</p>
<p>This is also where the surf instructors hang out after work, so if you want a real conversation about the next morning's break, this is the calmer corner to sit at.</p>
<h2>The Long Beach Sunset Bars</h2>
<p>If you want a quieter night than the Urbiztondo strip, the Long Beach hotel row in Bauang (20 minutes south) has the calmer beachfront bars with the swimming pools that kids actually use during the day. The bars there are mostly resort-attached, so the vibe is more family-trip than surf-town party. A good base if you came up to La Union with elders or small children but still want one chill night out.</p>
<p>Halo-Halo de Iloko in San Fernando city, 15 minutes from both San Juan and Bauang, is the dessert stop after dinner. The Ilocos halo-halo with longganisa-flavored ice cream is the order; the shop closes by 9 PM, so go right after dinner.</p>
<h2>Getting There and Back</h2>
<p>Partas, Genesis, and Victory Liner from Cubao or Pasay take 5 to 6 hours overnight. The TPLEX shortcut cuts drive time to 4 to 4.5 hours if you have a car. From La Union Bauang you can jeepney up to San Juan in 20 minutes. <a href="https://www.partas.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Partas</a> has the most slots; check schedules online before you go.</p>
<p>For the bars, the night scene runs late but the tricycles back to your hostel get scarce after midnight. Stay on the actual beach (Urbiztondo or Bauang) if you want to walk back to your room. If you stayed in San Fernando city for quieter rooms, plan the Grab back early or split the fare with a barkada.</p>
<h2>What to Drink and Eat</h2>
<p>San Miguel Pale Pilsen is the universal order at every bar in town. Local craft beers on tap at El Union and at a couple of the surf-shack bars are the more interesting drinks. For food, the late-night grills serve tuna sashimi, calamares, and sisig that handle the post-bar hunger. Breakfast the next morning is longganisa Vigan-style with sukang Iloko at any San Juan carinderia.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>October through March is the big surf season and the busiest bar nights. December and January are the peak; the surf crowd is at full capacity and Friday-Saturday nights run packed. April through September is calmer; the bars stay open but the crowds are smaller. Avoid Holy Week unless you booked rooms three months out.</p>
<p>The San Juan bar scene is the rare Philippine night scene that does not feel forced. The bars came up around the surf community, not around tourists, and the difference shows. Come for the waves, stay for the night that runs late and feels like a small town's barkada bonfire scaled up.</p>
